title: For Sale:  U.S.M.C. Springfield M1A 308 Walnut lots of extras
postcontent: Custom engraved Springfield Armory M1A with lots of extras included. The rifle is the full length barrel with Walnut stock. Condition of entire gun is very good, U.S.M.C logo and inscription have been laser engraved in the rear of the stock. Cleaning kit is brand new and never been installed in the gun. The scope mount is a Gen 4 Springfield Aluminum mount that is also brand new never installed. This gun has had the bolt locking lugs professionally lapped to the receiver to ensure full bearing on both lugs. This is a process of lapping the lugs while spring pressure dives the bolt back, and ensuring proper head space is maintained. The lapping ensures safety and precision as the bolt locking lugs fully share the bolt thrust during the firing cycle. The amount of head space is about 1.63 which puts this at a chamber dimension consistent with that used by the military. It is not excessively tight, but will chamber either NATO 7.62X51 or .308 Win. without overpressure or carbon build up causing clearance issues. This is a very shootable gun. I have sighted it in per the military field manual for M80 147 gr. ball ammo. Elevation adjustments are dead on, I have shot it out as far as 500 yards open sight with precision you would expect from this gun. Also included will be the manuals, the lock, the padded travel case, the military standard marksman sling, 2 original 10 round magazines from Springfield Armory, as well as the scope mount with Leupold rings, and the cleaning kit. Overall this is a very unique, field ready rifle. I will ship all the associated parts to your personal address, the gun will ship in the case to your FFL, all shipping will be covered by a flat fee of $50.

Like stagecoaches, swinging saloon doors and Pony Express riders, there are many innovations of the Old West that have long faded from use and live on only in Western movies and history books.

But there are still a few frontier staples that were so effective and ahead of their time that they remain in use today. Take, for instance, the intimidating octagonal barrels commonly found on the repeating rifles of that period. These heavy-duty workhorses sported added mass and extra weight to aid in heat absorption, making them the forerunners to the bull barrels used on modern target and varmint rifles.
